skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "ecc7c4f1-c075-4412-9187-63c77a7fc00b", "value": "The British Admiralty in practice used a fathom of 6 feet. This was despite its being \u200a1\u20441000 of a nautical mile (i.e. 6.08 feet) until the adoption of the international nautical mile."}
{"id": "cd0d41f2-872d-403a-98a2-0785f079dda6", "value": "\u200a1\u2044100 of a chain and \u200a1\u20441000 of a furlong."}

{"id": "5396abe3-cfa4-403c-8828-bb242b5064aa", "value": "Used for measuring distances at sea. Until the adoption of the international definition of 1852 metres in 1970, the British nautical (Admiralty) mile was defined as 6080 feet."}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "dac73c67-6a36-476a-9ffc-f90332f340a3", "value": "A unit of weight in the avoirdupois system equal to 2,240 pounds (1,016.05 kg) in Britain (the long ton) and 2,000 pounds (907.18 kg) in the United States (the short ton). \nAs a unit of volume it is equivalent to 100 cubic feet (the register ton) or 40 cubic feet (the freight or measurement ton)"}

skos:Concept.skos:definition: {"id": "d6c43254-6041-4434-a3a2-bead9d5abe19", "value": "100 links, 4 rods or \u200a1\u204410 of a furlong. The distance between the two wickets on a cricket pitch."}
{"id": "045be35a-9e5f-4430-8b1d-1f4161698236", "value": "The rod is also called pole or perch and equal to \u200a5 1\u20442 yards"}
{"id": "e17bbdf6-6009-48dd-8e50-e97a0f34f4ca", "value": "One tenth of a nautical mile. Equal to 100 fathoms under the strict definition."}
{"id": "2ad104b4-322c-4f71-9bdf-4ecb1e0d0dff", "value": "1/12000 of a foot or 25.4 \u03bcm. Also known as mil"}
{"id": "38959fcc-db5e-401e-97dc-1b087eb6c582", "value": "Defined as exactly 0.9144 metres by the International yard and pound agreement of 1959"}

{"id": "a2cf87c3-17e7-4c0f-9947-87c976fc5c16", "value": "Although the proper term is square rod, for centuries this unit has been called a pole or perch or, more properly, square pole or square perch."}
{"id": "5d05f9e2-9f37-44c2-9dba-83d31d99730c", "value": "Traditionally 3 miles. No longer an official unit in any nation."}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "2eabe723-194e-4737-bd6e-57e4ca46e2c5", "value": "The SI derived unit of specific volume."}

{"id": "c50d3df0-fb3a-4cf9-8db6-9809beef6b60", "value": "There are certain units, which are accepted for use with the SI. It includes units which are in continuous everyday use, in particular the traditional units of time and of angle, together with a few other units which have assumed increasing technical importance. There are also units which are currently accepted for use with the SI to satisfy the needs of commercial, legal and specialist scientific interests or are important for the interpretation of older texts."}
{"id": "9d88f0d4-0b65-4903-9efd-0ef195202fcb", "value": "The SI derived unit for current density."}
{"id": "4aacd9d5-469a-4edf-82e2-843bb8fb7f7a", "value": "The SI derived unit of speed or velocity"}
{"id": "bda6d4f4-e48d-4d67-a977-08fb3f6833c4", "value": "The SI derived unit for density or mass density."}
{"id": "493b2c7c-a303-4858-87d1-b8a7fe25ab87", "value": "The SI derived unit for the refractive index."}
{"id": "97b423a0-30aa-460e-a532-19f04297f7da", "value": "The SI derived unit of magnetic field strength."}
{"id": "121ae2d5-7824-4754-b777-e4620f554bd5", "value": "The SI derived unit of concentration (of amount of a substance)."}
